{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502083"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:39:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:39:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1825"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1825"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.18,0.01,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1825"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114944"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1825","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1825"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1825"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96950"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"451"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7665"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7773"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42411"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114944"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman presents with a lesion on her lower lip (Image). The lesion has been slowly increasing in size and sometimes bleeds. She does not remember it being associated with any pain or itch. She has had some \u0022sores\u0022 removed before but cannot remember what the doctor called them.\u00a0She worked as a farmhand for 30 years before retiring in the city. Her medical history includes hypertension, and osteoarthritis, and regular medications are ramipril and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the lesion located on the left bottom lip. It is plaque-like, round and relatively symmetrical.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Squamous cell carcinoma","Basal cell carcinoma","Melanoma","Herpes simplex virus","Seborrhoeic keratosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis lesion has all characteristics consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Esquamous cell carcinoma \u003C/strong\u003E(SCC). These skin cancers are associated with sun exposure and seen most often in older patients and those with light skin. They typically present as a red, crusty lesion that grow slowly. They can be painful and bleed easily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinoma \u003C/strong\u003E(BCC) presents as a pink lesion with a pearly appearance and typically have a raised, rolled edges. They have many small blood vessels (telangiectasias) and a clearly defined margin. BCC is a differential for this lesion, however given the obvious hyperkeratosis, SCC is the most likely diagnosis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeborrhoeic keratoses \u003C/strong\u003Etypically are hyperpigmented and waxy, and appear to be \u0022stuck-on\u0022. They have a variety of colours (skin coloured to black/brown) and as they can resemble melanoma or SCC. If there is concern about the diagnosis, a biopsy is prudent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMelanoma \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be characterised based on the \u0022A-E\u0022 approach - asymmetrical, border irregularity, colour variability, diameter \u0026gt;6mm and evolving. Amelanotic melanoma is an important differential in a new, growing skin-coloured nodule, but is not the most likely diagnosis here. Family history should also be assessed when monitoring for melanomas. If there is any suspicion for melanoma, lesions should always be biopsied.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex virus \u003C/strong\u003Eor \u0027cold sores\u0027 is common in this site, however presents as a painful or itchy vesicular eruption which normally heals in 7-10 days. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Squamous cell carcinomas are typically painless ulcers found on the face and neck, that are non-healing and tend to bleed."],"references":["Trost J, Applebaum D, Orengo I. Common adult skin and soft tissue lesions. Semin Plast Surg [Internet]. 2016 [cited 2022 Nov 4];20(3):98-107. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4961504/ doi: 10.1055/s-0036-1584823"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96950"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1825"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18557"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18557"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3af2089d-8790-42ab-a43b-18e4ffa3d365.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3af2089d-8790-42ab-a43b-18e4ffa3d365.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96950"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T14:52:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T14:52:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1825"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114944"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes